## Definition of Done (Applies to All User Stories)

### Functional Completion
- All acceptance criteria are fully implemented and verified. For a userstory, all of its sub issuesÂ´ acceptance criteria needs to be implemented and verified. 
- Feature behaves as described in the user story on all supported devices and browsers.
- Edge cases and validation rules are handled correctly.

### Code Quality
- Code follows project coding standards and conventions.
- No critical or high-severity linting or static analysis issues remain.
- No hardcoded secrets, credentials, or environment-specific values.

### Testing
- Relevant unit tests are implemented and passing.
- Relevant integration tests are implemented and passing (where applicable).
- Feature has been manually tested by the developer.
- Regression testing confirms no existing functionality is broken.

### Security & Data Handling
- Input validation and sanitization are implemented where applicable.
- Authentication and authorization rules are respected.
- Sensitive data is stored and transmitted securely.
- No sensitive data is exposed in logs or client-side code.

### UX & Accessibility
- UI follows the approved design and UX guidelines.
- Error messages are clear, user-friendly, and actionable.
- Interactive elements meet accessibility and usability standards.
- Loading, empty, and error states are handled gracefully.

### Performance & Reliability
- Feature does not introduce noticeable performance degradation.
- API calls and background processes handle failures gracefully.
- No unnecessary network requests or re-renders.

### Documentation & Traceability
- Relevant documentation is updated (README, admin guide, or internal docs).
- User story is linked to the correct Epic.

### Deployment Readiness
- Feature is deployable without manual intervention.
- Feature works correctly in the target environment (staging/production).
- No feature flags or temporary code paths remain unless explicitly approved.
